To find the probability of getting at least two heads when flipping six coins, we can use the concept of complementary probability.  

* **Calculate the probability of the event *not* happening:** This means finding the probability of getting fewer than two heads, which is the same as getting either zero or one head.

* **Probability of zero heads:**  There's only one way to get all tails (TTTTTT), and 64 total possible outcomes. So, the probability of zero heads is 1/64.

* **Probability of one head:** There are six ways to get one head (HTTTTT, THTTTT, etc.), so the probability of one head is 6/64.

* **Probability of fewer than two heads:** Add the probabilities of zero and one head: 1/64 + 6/64 = 7/64

* **Probability of at least two heads:**  Subtract the probability of fewer than two heads from 1 (representing all possible outcomes): 1 - 7/64 = 57/64




\begin{equation*}
\boxed{\frac{57}{64}}
\end{equation*}

